kitty v0.47.4: let a center-edge layer-shell panel cover the menu bar strip.

Upstream _glfwPlatformSetLayerShellConfig sizes GLFW_EDGE_CENTER (and
LAYER_SHELL_BACKGROUND) panels to the screen height minus the menu bar, so a
panel pinned to the Xeneon Edge leaves a dead strip at the top of the glass.
Panels are placed at NSPopUpMenuWindowLevel - 1, above the menu bar, so
covering the full frame is safe; the now-unused dock_height/menubar_height
locals are dropped to keep the build warning-clean.

Sizing alone is not enough (v1 regression, eyes-on 2026-07-03): the full-frame
rect submitted via setFrame: goes through AppKit's default
constrainFrameRect:toScreen:, which pushes a frame whose top overlaps the menu
bar back down below it -- origin shifts, size intact -- so the 24-row panel
rendered shifted with the bar still visible and the bottom row off the glass.
kitty's GlfwWindow already overrides constrainFrameRect: to honor
ns.suppress_frame_constraints (used transiently for traditional-fullscreen
restoration, #9572); set it permanently for full-cover panels so every
constraint pass (setStyleMask:, setFrame:, orderFront:, screen changes) leaves
the frame alone.

Generated against https://raw.githubusercontent.com/kovidgoyal/kitty/v0.47.4/glfw/cocoa_window.m
(sha1 84e821e4e6b9e131fbcaa9ff991dff27183d24dc). Applied by overlay.nix.

--- a/glfw/cocoa_window.m
+++ b/glfw/cocoa_window.m
@@ -2681,11 +2681,16 @@
     double spacing_y = top_edge_spacing + bottom_edge_spacing;
     const unsigned xsz = config.x_size_in_pixels ? (unsigned)(config.x_size_in_pixels * xscale) : (cell_width * config.x_size_in_cells);
     const unsigned ysz = config.y_size_in_pixels ? (unsigned)(config.y_size_in_pixels * yscale) : (cell_height * config.y_size_in_cells);
-    CGFloat dock_height = NSMinY(screen.visibleFrame) - NSMinY(screen.frame);
-    CGFloat menubar_height = NSHeight(screen.frame) - NSHeight(screen.visibleFrame) - dock_height;
     CGFloat x = NSMinX(screen.visibleFrame), y = NSMinY(screen.visibleFrame) - 1, width = NSWidth(screen.visibleFrame), height = NSHeight(screen.visibleFrame) + 2;
     if (config.type == GLFW_LAYER_SHELL_BACKGROUND || config.edge == GLFW_EDGE_CENTER) {
-        x = NSMinX(screen.frame); height = NSHeight(screen.frame) - menubar_height + 1; y = NSMinY(screen.frame); width = NSWidth(screen.frame);
+        // khudson: cover the full display height, menu bar strip included.
+        // Panels draw at NSPopUpMenuWindowLevel - 1, above the menu bar, so a
+        // center-edge panel can own every pixel of the target display.
+        // AppKit's default constrainFrameRect:toScreen: pushes a frame whose
+        // top overlaps the menu bar back down below it (origin shifts, size
+        // intact), so make the GlfwWindow override return frames untouched.
+        window->ns.suppress_frame_constraints = true;
+        x = NSMinX(screen.frame); height = NSHeight(screen.frame); y = NSMinY(screen.frame); width = NSWidth(screen.frame);
     }
